{"cursor":"10203","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'McCuneâReischauer romanization' is one of the two most widely-used Korean\nlanguage romanization systems, along with the Revised Romanization of Korean,\nwhich replaced (a modified) McCuneâReischauer as the official romanization\nsystem in South Korea in 2000. A variant of McCuneâReischauer is used as the\nofficial system in North Korea.\n\nThe system was created in 1937 by two Americans, George M. McCune and Edwin O.\nReischauer. With a few exceptions, it does not attempt to transliterate Korean\ntext but rather to represent the phonetic pronunciation. McCuneâReischauer is\nwidely used outside of Korea. A variant of it was used as the official\nromanization system in South Korea from 1984 to 2000. A third system — the\nYale Romanization system, which is a transliteration system — exists, but\nis used only in academic literature, especially in linguistics. During the\nperiod of Russian interest in Korea at the beginning of the 20th century,\nattempts were also made at representing Korean in Cyrillic.\n","linknr":180,"url":"McCune-Reischauer","recorded":1375075054,"links":["/w/index.php?title=McCune%E2%80%93Reischauer&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=McCune%E2%80%93Reischauer&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/McCune%E2%80%93Reischauer","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modu